{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01XXCvGy94BxFkUQUrtfLurL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze this content moderation service task and reason through each behavior to understand the minimum test infrastructure needed.\n\nThe system:\n- Receives user-submitted images and text posts\n- Uses AI vision model to classify images\n- Uses AI text model to classify text\n- Posts flagged by either model are held for human review\n- Must handle high throughput during peak hours\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n1. **An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n   - Key question: Does this depend on what the AI vision model returns?\n   - The behavior is: explicit image → AI model returns \"explicit\" → system flags it and holds it\n   - Could a mock miss this? A mock that always returns \"explicit\" would pass, but the REAL behavior is that the model might not classify it correctly\n   - But wait - the question is whether the IMAGE is actually explicit. The system receives an image and calls the AI vision model.\n   - So the test is: \"when an image containing explicit content is submitted, the system flags it\"\n   - The failure mode: the system receives explicit content but doesn't flag it\n   - This depends on: (1) the AI model correctly classifying the image as explicit, (2) the system correctly handling that classification and flagging it\n   - Could a pure in-process mock miss this? \n     - A mock that always returns \"explicit\" would verify the flagging logic works\n     - But a REAL failure would be: the AI model doesn't classify it as explicit, or the system mishandles the response\n   - The real failure boundary is: does the system correctly FLAG an image when the AI model says it's explicit?\n     - Mock can catch: system doesn't flag when AI says \"explicit\"\n     - Mock can't catch: AI model doesn't actually classify explicit content correctly\n   - But the BEHAVIOR is about the image \"containing explicit content\" - this implies we're testing whether the system catches explicit content\n   - So the real failure is: explicit image goes through without being flagged\n   - To verify this works, I need the actual AI vision model to classify the image, not just a stub returning \"explicit\". A mock only validates the downstream flagging logic, but misses whether the model itself detects explicit content. This requires an AGENTIC test—submitting a real explicit image to the actual AI model to confirm it's caught.\n\n2. **A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).**\n   - This also hinges on the AI text model's capability. The system needs to recognize hate speech even when users try to evade detection through character substitution or unicode tricks. A mock returning \"hate_speech\" would only test the flagging mechanism, not whether the model handles obfuscation. The real test requires the actual AI model to process obfuscated hate speech and correctly identify it, making this another AGENTIC-level concern.\n\n3. **A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n   - Here I'm testing the decision logic: clean image + clean text → publish. I can mock both AI models to return \"clean\" and verify the system publishes instead of holding or dropping. This is purely about the conditional logic, independent of the AI models' actual performance. This fits UNIT or INTEGRATION level—UNIT if testing just the publish decision, INTEGRATION if running through the full moderation pipeline with mocked calls. Given the issue mentions the full pipeline, this is likely INTEGRATION, though the core behavior being validated is the decision logic itself.\n\n4. **The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.**\n   - Latency requirements can't be tested with mocks because the timing depends on actual AI model response times and network calls. I need to invoke the real external APIs to measure whether the pipeline truly meets the 5-second threshold. This is SYSTEM level testing.\n\n5. **When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.**\n   - I can mock the vision model to throw an exception and verify the system queues for retry instead of auto-approving. The logic being tested—handling failure gracefully by queueing rather than defaulting to approval—is independent of the real model's behavior. A mock exception is sufficient to validate this error-handling path.\n\n6. **The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.**\n   - Consistency across multiple submissions depends entirely on how the real AI vision model classifies the same image. A deterministic mock would always pass this test, but the actual question is whether the real model returns the same classification each time. I need to submit the same image multiple times to the real service to see if it produces consistent results. This is SYSTEM level because it's testing the AI model's own behavior.\n\nThe next consideration is whether caching plays a role—if the system caches decisions, consistency would be guaranteed regardless of the model's actual behavior. But the core test is about the AI model's consistency, which makes it fundamentally dependent on the real service's output. Whether this is INTEGRATION or AGENTIC depends on whether I'm testing the cache logic alongside the model, or just the model's consistency itself.\n\nFor the explicit image behavior, I need a real explicit image and the actual vision model to properly verify detection. Mocking the model's response would mask whether the real model actually catches it. The system must receive the image, call the real AI service, and flag it based on the actual classification—this is AGENTIC since it hinges on the real model's capability. The same logic applies to hate speech with obfuscation: the system needs the real model to detect the masked content.\n\nFor the clean post scenario, both checks passing and triggering publication is testable with mocked AI responses since I'm validating the conditional logic itself, not the model's accuracy. This drops to INTEGRATION level—the full pipeline runs with simulated models.\n\nLatency requirements demand real API calls; mocks would show near-instant responses and completely miss the actual performance characteristics. That's SYSTEM level. Similarly, when the vision model becomes unavailable, I could mock an exception to verify the retry-queue logic, but real timeout behavior and connection failures might behave differently than a simple mock exception. The realistic handling of actual service degradation requires observing how the system responds to genuine unavailability scenarios.\n\nFor consistency across identical images, the test hinges on whether the AI model itself produces stable outputs and whether any caching layer works correctly. A deterministic mock would always succeed, masking potential variance in the real model's responses. This depends on the actual AI model's behavior, making it AGENTIC level.\n\nReconsidering the minimum levels: explicit content detection fundamentally requires the real vision model to determine whether it actually catches what it's supposed to catch. The core question isn't whether the system routes the flagged result correctly—it's whether the model itself identifies explicit material. That's AGENTIC minimum. - Act: Submit the image to the system\n- Assert: Verify it gets flagged and held from publication\n\nTo validate the system handles real explicit images correctly, I need both an actual explicit image and the real AI vision model making the determination. This requires AGENTIC level testing.\n\nFor behavior 2 around obfuscated hate speech, the same logic applies—the AI model must genuinely detect the violation, so AGENTIC level is necessary at 70% probability, with Integration and System levels at 10% and 15% respectively due to their inability to catch real model failures.\n\nBehavior 3 differs fundamentally since it's straightforward logic validation without reliance on external AI classification.\n\nI can mock both the image and text classifiers to return \"clean\" results, then verify the system publishes the post. The real failure modes here are the system failing to publish when both checks pass, or incorrectly holding/dropping it instead. Mocked AI models suffice to catch these logic errors at INTEGRATION level.\n\nThe question becomes whether I should also test with real AI models to ensure genuinely clean posts actually get published. The behavior specifies \"a post that passes both content checks\"—fundamentally a logic test. Mocked models validate this. Real models would add confidence but aren't required for the core logic failure. The minimum sufficient level is INTEGRATION at 70%, though Unit testing could cover the publish decision as a single function at 20%. System and Agentic levels drop to 5% each since the logic doesn't depend on real AI classification, and Workflow testing isn't applicable here.\n\nFor the latency requirement, I need real end-to-end execution with actual AI API calls to measure whether the system stays under 5 seconds. Real failures would be slow AI models or inefficient processing. This is SYSTEM level—testing against real external APIs and their actual response times. The distinction matters: if the concern is how long real API calls take, that's System level; if it's how AI model behavior varies and affects latency on different inputs, that's Agentic level. The minimum is System at around 75%, with Agentic at 20% accounting for model behavior variation, and Unit/Integration at 5% since they can't measure real API latency.\n\nFor the vision model unavailability scenario, I'm considering what \"unavailable\" actually means—network timeouts, 503 errors, connection refused, real service down. A mocked exception catches some cases, but testing against actual service unavailability gives more confidence in realistic failure handling. This pushes toward SYSTEM level testing, though a well-designed mock exception can cover the core logic at INTEGRATION level.\n\nTo verify the real failure—that the system auto-approves when it shouldn't—I need to make the vision model unavailable, submit an image, and confirm it gets queued rather than approved. The minimum is INTEGRATION with a mock raising an exception, but SYSTEM testing with genuine unavailability is more robust.\n\nAdjusting the probabilities: Unit at 10% since error handling might be isolated, INTEGRATION and SYSTEM both at 40% as viable approaches, AGENTIC at 5% since this isn't about model behavior variation, and WORKFLOW at 5% for a single-step flow.\n\nActually, reconsidering the core question—whether the system correctly handles unavailability—a mock exception can catch the logic failure, making INTEGRATION sufficient. However, real network scenarios might expose timeout or connection issues the mock misses. The minimum viable level is INTEGRATION, but SYSTEM provides higher confidence in production-like conditions.\n\nFor the probabilities: INTEGRATION at 65% as the practical minimum, SYSTEM at 20% for realistic scenarios, with UNIT, AGENTIC, and WORKFLOW each at 5% since they don't directly address the unavailability handling.\n\nMoving to behavior 6 about borderline image consistency: the core challenge is whether the system returns the same moderation decision for identical images submitted in quick succession. Non-deterministic AI responses require the real model (AGENTIC level), while caching failures need the full system integration. Testing involves submitting the same borderline image twice and verifying consistent results. A mocked AI can validate caching logic works, but only the real model reveals if the AI itself produces variable classifications.\n\nThe consistency question really hinges on two layers: whether the system caches decisions (INTEGRATION concern) and whether the AI model itself is deterministic (AGENTIC concern). Given the high-throughput context mentioned earlier, caching is probably implemented, making INTEGRATION the practical minimum to catch logic failures. Unit tests alone miss both the caching mechanism and any AI variability, so they're unlikely to surface real issues here.\n\nAdjusting the probabilities: Integration should be higher at 55% since caching is likely present, System drops to 15% for the real model's response characteristics, Agentic stays around 25% for model consistency across calls, and Workflow remains minimal at 5%. the structured test plan response.\n\nI need to reconsider my approach here. The instructions emphasize testing for real failures that could occur in production, not just verifying happy-path scenarios.\n\nFor behavior 1 (explicit image flagged), the actual failures I should be concerned about are: the system failing to properly flag a vision model response, the vision model itself missing explicit content in a real image, or the system publishing despite a flag being set. Catching the first requires integration-level testing with a mocked vision model, but catching the second requires an agentic test with real images and a real model. The third could be caught at integration or higher levels. To catch all realistic failure modes, I need to think about what's the minimum sufficient level.\n\nFor behavior 2 (hate speech with obfuscation), the same logic applies—I need real models to verify they can actually detect obfuscated hate speech.\n\nFor behavior 3 (clean post published), the real failures are different: the system might skip calling the models entirely, it might incorrectly flag clean content, or it might drop clean posts without publishing. An integration test with mocked models can catch the first and third, but the second failure—false positives from the AI models themselves—depends on the actual models' behavior. If the vision or text model has a high false positive rate on clean content, that's a real production failure I need to account for. This suggests I might need agentic-level testing to verify clean posts pass through reliably with real models.\n\nBut the behavior statement assumes the post passes both checks. With mocked models that always return clean, I'm testing the system logic. The question seems to be asking for the minimum level to catch failures in the system itself, not in the AI models' accuracy.\n\nSo my assessment: behavior 1 and 2 require agentic testing because they depend on real model capabilities. Behavior 3 can be integration-level since I'm testing whether the system correctly publishes when checks pass. Behavior 4 needs system-level testing for actual latency. Behavior 5 works at integration with mocked unavailability. For behavior 6, I need to think about whether the system caches decisions or re-evaluates each time—if it caches, consistency is automatic; if not, I'm testing whether the real model gives the same output for the same input.\n\nGiven the high-throughput context, caching is probably implemented. But without knowing the exact design, I'd estimate integration-level testing at 45% likelihood, agentic at 35%, system at 10%, with unit and workflow making up the remainder.\n\nThe core question is whether the system produces consistent outputs for the same input. If caching exists, determinism is enforced. If not, the AI model's non-deterministic behavior becomes the limiting factor—especially for borderline images where classification confidence is low.\n\nThree failure modes emerge: uncached systems where the AI varies its classification, cache implementations with improper image keys, and time-based caches expiring prematurely. Testing the first requires agentic-level evaluation with a real model. The other two can be caught at integration level with mocked AI and cache logic verification. Since both levels are needed to cover all scenarios, the minimum testing requirement likely spans both integration and agentic approaches. is sufficient since we're just verifying the system routes flagged images correctly. The minimum level is INTEGRATION.\n\nFor behavior 2, detecting subtle nudity requires the actual vision model's judgment on edge cases, pushing this to SYSTEM level. Behavior 3 similarly needs real model behavior for borderline content decisions, also SYSTEM. Behavior 4's latency requirement demands real external API calls to measure actual performance, making it SYSTEM as well. Behavior 5 tests cache effectiveness with repeated requests, which INTEGRATION can handle with mocked responses. Behavior 6 involves consistent decisions on ambiguous images, requiring the real model's behavior—AGENTIC level. -MISS: Could a mock miss this? Not really - mock can raise exception\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it need real service unavailability? Not necessarily - exception handling is sufficient\n- MOCK-HIDE: Could mocking hide real failure? Only if real unavailability behaves differently\n- LLM-DEP: No, about error handling, not model accuracy\n- Minimum: INTEGRATION (mock exception) or SYSTEM (real unavailability)\n\nFor behavior 5, I think the minimum is INTEGRATION because mocking the unavailability (via exception) is sufficient to test the logic. However, SYSTEM level provides more realistic testing.\n\nI'll say INTEGRATION is minimum.\n\n**Behavior 6: Borderline image consistency**\n- MOCK-MISS: Yes, deterministic mock always returns same result\n- REAL-INFRA: Yes, need real vision API\n- MOCK-HIDE: Yes, mock hides AI model's potential non-determinism\n- LLM-DEP: Yes, correctness depends on vision model being deterministic or system caching\n- Minimum: INTEGRATION (with caching) or AGENTIC (without caching)\n\nThe minimum here hinges on whether caching is implemented. With caching in place, INTEGRATION suffices. Without it, I'd need AGENTIC to verify the model's consistency. Given this uncertainty, I'm distributing probabilities across levels: Integration at 50% (assuming caching exists), Agentic at 35% (model consistency verification), System at 10% (real infrastructure), Unit at 5%, and Workflow at 0%.\n\nReconsidering behavior 5—when the vision model becomes unavailable, the system should queue image posts for retry rather than auto-approving them. The core risks are logic failures (auto-approving anyway or failing to queue properly) and infrastructure failures (timeouts or crashes). INTEGRATION testing with mocked unavailability can catch the logic issues, while SYSTEM testing would be needed to validate realistic timeout behavior. The minimum is INTEGRATION, though SYSTEM provides better coverage for infrastructure edge cases.\n\nFor behavior 4, measuring the 5-second latency requirement means capturing end-to-end response time from submission to completion. INTEGRATION testing with mocked API calls and artificial delays can verify the threshold, but SYSTEM testing with real external calls would be more realistic for catching actual performance bottlenecks.\n\nI'm settling on SYSTEM as the minimum viable level since mocked delays don't reflect real network conditions or service load that could cause failures in production. The latency risk is fundamentally about real-world performance, not simulated timing.\n\nAssigning probabilities for behavior 4:\n- Unit: 0%\n- Integration: 15%\n- System: 70%\n- Agentic: 10%\n- Workflow: 5%\n\nNow reconsidering behaviors 1 and 2 to determine if they should be SYSTEM rather than AGENTIC. For behavior 1, the explicit content detection depends on whether the image classification itself is the critical component or if the broader system integration matters more. The core issue is distinguishing between SYSTEM and AGENTIC levels. A real HTTP call to a vision API is SYSTEM-level, but the vision model's actual classification of explicit content is AGENTIC-level since it depends on the model's learned behavior. Given the failure mode centers on the model's classification accuracy rather than just the API call itself, AGENTIC seems more precise. The definitions clarify that AGENTIC covers real AI/ML model calls like classification APIs, which directly applies here—the test's success hinges on whether the vision model correctly identifies explicit images, not merely on making the HTTP request.\n\nFor the text model scenario, the same logic applies: the failure point is the model's inability to detect obfuscated hate speech, which is a model-level issue, not a system-level one. Both behaviors depend on the actual model's performance, so both map to AGENTIC. The remaining behaviors fall into INTEGRATION and SYSTEM categories based on whether they involve cross-component interactions or external dependencies.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12610,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12610},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"975820a2-75f2-4e43-8b9b-8b43e228b84c","uuid":"dff508f4-4ee0-4713-91d7-4217ee53f77f"}
